    <text>
        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>244 West 52.<lb/>
                New York.<lb/>
                Sept 8&#47;80<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
                Rev. and dear sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Although the New Year<lb/> has commenced I trust it is yet<lb/> time to express a wish that its growth<lb/> may witness your family&#39;s prosperity&#44;<lb/> and that the blessing of our Father<lb/> may rest upon your labors.<lb/></p>
            <p>I arrived Sunday week&#44;<lb/> or rather Monday in New York&#44; and<lb/> found my hands well occupied&#59;  I<lb/> received a letter from your son<lb/> on the Eve of my departure for<lb/> England&#44; but whether I acknowledged<lb/> it or not I cannot recall&#59; if I did<lb/> not&#44; then I must apologize to him&#44; so<lb/> kindly discover for me whether I<lb/> have been guilty of discourtesy or<lb/> not.<lb/></p>
            <p>I regret to say that<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>2.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>my father has been very ill&#44; but I<lb/> hear is progressing&#59; I left him<lb/> almost immediately after the crisis<lb/> was passed&#44; having to leave England<lb/> a little earlier owing to an accident<lb/> to the steamer on which my passage<lb/> was engaged and the substitution of<lb/> a slower boat which would have<lb/> landed me too near the Holy days.<lb/></p>
            <p>I much regret the changes in<lb/> 44<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St&#59;&#45;&#45;what can be done to revive<lb/> an interest in our faith without pandering<lb/> to those whose religion is not deep seated<lb/> enough to make them actual Jews and<lb/> Jewesses&#44; but whose very attendance at<lb/> a place of worship must be bought by novelty<lb/> and attraction&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I find in England a feeling in<lb/> favor of change&#44; but not to the extent<lb/> American Judaism favors.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>3<lb/></p>
            <p>I wish some means could be<lb/> applied to mitigate the evil<lb/> of congregational legislation in<lb/> Jewish ritual and such matters.<lb/></p>
            <p>Do you not think an outspoken<lb/> condemnation by our <hi rend="underline">chief</hi> Rabbis<lb/> would at least open the eyes of the<lb/> thinking part of our community.<lb/>  For instance pews are condemned<lb/> by Dr Adler of London&#44; Isidor of France&#44;<lb/> Dunner of Holland&#44; Levi of Corfa&#91;&#63;&#93;&#44;<lb/> and others of repute far greater<lb/> than American Reform&#45;ministers.<lb/>  The organ also&#44; except by Astrue late<lb/> of Belgium&#44; and Isidor&#44; who however<lb/> do not speak at all warmly of it<lb/></p>
            <p>It does seem to me so sinful<lb/> that the conservation of Judaism<lb/> and Jewish customs should not<lb/> be the common care of all Jews<lb/> in all parts of the world.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>4.<lb/></p>
            <p>All religious societies have organization&#44;<lb/> ours excepted&#59; our policy seems to be<lb/> fold arms and be still&#44; while the sheep<lb/> get loose&#44; feed on pastures new and dan<lb/>gerous&#59; and are exposed to shepherds like<lb/> certain ones of old.<lb/></p>
            <p>Is there no way of curing the<lb/> evil&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have no doubt you have<lb/> thought much upon the subject&#59; if<lb/> at your leisure you would express<lb/> yourself as to what your views are with<lb/> regard to interesting European Jews<lb/> in our condition&#44; I should indeed<lb/> be only <sic>to</sic> happy to assist in furthering<lb/> them&#44; being amused that you are not<lb/> an advocate of the laissez&#45;aller policy.<lb/></p>
            <p>With kind regards to your<lb/> son<lb/>
                I am dear sir<lb/>
                yrs vy truly<lb/>
                H P Mendes<lb/></p>
        </body>
